### \#\#\# Real Life Example

If I give you a \*\*cake\*\*, it needs a \*\*container\*\* to protect it during transport. Without the container, the cake could get damaged, contaminated, or ruined by external factors like dust, weather, or handling.

### \#\#\# How This Relates to Docker:

\- \*\*Cake\*\*: Your application (code, dependencies, libraries).  
\- \*\*Container\*\*: Docker container that wraps and protects your application.  
\- \*\*Environment\*\*: The outside world (different operating systems, servers, or machines).

The container ensures that the cake (application) remains intact and works the same way, no matter where it is delivered. It isolates the cake from external factors, just like Docker containers isolate your application from the host system.

### \#\#\# Example:

Imagine you have a web application:  
1\. Without Docker: If you try to run the app on another machine, it might fail because the machine doesn't have the right dependencies or configurations.  
2\. With Docker: The app is packaged in a container with everything it needs, so it runs perfectly on any machine with Docker installed—just like a cake in a container stays safe during transport.

### \#\#\# Key Concept:

Docker containers ensure your "cake" (application) is portable, consistent, and protected, no matter where it is delivered or run.

Docker Commands  
Always append “- \- help” at last of a command to know its details

## **🐳 `docker ps` – Listing Running Containers**

The `docker ps` command displays information about active Docker containers on your system. It's akin to the Unix `ps` command, which lists running processes.

### **🔍 Basic Usage**

bash  
CopyEdit  
`docker ps`

This command outputs a table with details about each running container:

* **CONTAINER ID**: Unique identifier for the container.

* **IMAGE**: The Docker image the container is based on.

* **COMMAND**: The command executed when the container starts.

* **CREATED**: Time elapsed since the container was created.

* **STATUS**: Current status (e.g., Up, Exited).

* **PORTS**: Port mappings between the host and the container.

* **NAMES**: Automatically assigned or user-defined container name.

*Note*: By default, `docker ps` shows only running containers.

---

## **🛠️ Common Options**

Enhance the `docker ps` command with these options:

`-a` or `--all`: Show all containers (default shows just running  
`docker ps -a`

* 

`-q` or `--quiet`: Display only container IDs.  
`docker ps -q`

* 

`-l` or `--latest`: Show the most recently created container (includes all states  
`docker ps -l`

* 

`-n <number>` or `--last <number>`: Show the last `<number>` created containers (includes all states).  
`docker ps -n 5`

* 

`--no-trunc`: Don't truncate output (e.g., show full container IDs  
`docker ps --no-trunc`

* 

`-s` or `--size`: Display total file sizes  
`docker ps -s`

* 

`--format`: Format the output using a Go template  
`docker ps --format "table {{.ID}}\t{{.Names}}\t{{.Status}}"`

* `--filter` or `-f`: Filter output based on conditions  
  `docker ps --filter "status=exited"`

**🐳 1\. `docker ps -qa`**

**Purpose**: Lists all Docker containers (both running and stopped) by their IDs.​

* `-q` or `--quiet`: Displays only the container IDs.

* `-a` or `--all`: Includes all containers, not just the running ones.​

**Example Output**:

`a1b2c3d4e5f6`  
`f6e5d4c3b2a1`

**Use Case**: Useful when you need a list of all container IDs for batch operations.​

### **🛑 2\. `docker stop <container_id>`**

**Purpose**: Stops a running Docker container gracefully.​

* Sends a `SIGTERM` signal to allow the container to shut down properly.

* After a grace period (default 10 seconds), if the container hasn't stopped, a `SIGKILL` is sent to force termination.​[Spacelift+2Docker Documentation+2DevOps School+2](https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/stop/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

**Example**:

`docker stop a1b2c3d4e5f6`

**Use Case**: When you need to stop a specific running container.​

---

### **🔁 3\. `docker ps -qa | xargs docker stop`**

**Purpose**: Stops all Docker containers (running and stopped).​

**Breakdown**:

* `docker ps -qa`: Lists all container IDs.

* `xargs docker stop`: Passes each ID to `docker stop` to stop the containers.​[CSDN Blog+5Bobby Iliev Blog+5SupportFly+5](https://blog.bobby.sh/how-to-change-the-docker-ps-output-format?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

**Example**:

`docker ps -qa | xargs docker stop`

**Use Case**: Efficiently stops all containers in one command.​[Linuxier](https://linuxier.com/how-to-exit-a-docker-container-like-a-pro/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

### **🔍 4\. `docker ps -a | grep inv`**

**Purpose**: Filters the list of all containers to show only those with names or details containing the string "inv".​

**Breakdown**:

* `docker ps -a`: Lists all containers with detailed information.

* `grep inv`: Filters the output to lines containing "inv".​

**Example**:

`docker ps -a | grep inv`

**Use Case**: Helps identify containers related to a specific project or naming convention.​[Sematext](https://sematext.com/blog/docker-logs-location/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

### **🐳 1\. `docker logs test-mongo`**

**Purpose**: Displays the logs (standard output and error) of the container named `test-mongo`.​

**Usage**:

**Explanation**: This command retrieves the logs generated by the `test-mongo` container. It's useful for debugging or monitoring the container's output.​

### **📺 2\. `docker logs -f test-mongo`**

**Purpose**: Streams the logs of `test-mongo` in real-time.​

**Usage**:

`docker logs -f test-mongo`

**Explanation**: The `-f` (or `--follow`) flag allows you to continuously view new log entries as they are written, similar to the `tail -f` command in Unix/Linux. This is helpful for real-time monitoring.​

---

### **⏱️ 3\. `docker logs -ft test-mongo`**

**Purpose**: Streams the logs of `test-mongo` in real-time with timestamps.​

**Usage**:

`docker logs -ft test-mongo`

**Explanation**: Combining `-f` (follow) and `-t` (timestamps) flags, this command provides a real-time log stream with each entry prefixed by a timestamp, aiding in chronological analysis.

# **🐳 Docker Command Explained**

docker run \\  
\-d \\  
\--name test-mongo \\  
\-p 27018:27017 \\  
mongo

## **🔵 `docker run`**

* **Purpose**: Create and start a new container from an image.

* It **downloads the image** if not already available locally.

---

# **🛠️ Options used:**

| Part | Meaning |
| ----- | ----- |
| `-d` | **Detached mode** – run the container in the background (you get back your terminal). |
| `--name test-mongo` | **Names** the container `test-mongo` (instead of a random name). |
| `-p 27018:27017` | **Maps ports**: `Host port 27018` → `Container port 27017`. (Access MongoDB locally using 27018.) |
| `mongo` | **Image name** – tells Docker to use the `mongo` image (official MongoDB image). |

---

# **📈 After running**

* Docker creates a container named **`test-mongo`**.

* Internally, MongoDB listens at **27017**, but from outside (host system), you connect at **27018**.

* It runs in the background, and you get the container ID printed (like `493e4c63...`).

---

# **📌 Why Port Mapping?**

MongoDB default port \= **27017** inside the container.  
 You expose it as **27018** on your computer **to avoid conflicts** if your machine already has MongoDB installed.

# 

# **🐳 Updated Docker Command**

`docker run \`  
`-d \`  
`--name test-mongo \`  
`-p 27018:27017 \`  
`-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_USERNAME=root \`  
`-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_PASSWORD=example \`  
`mongo`

---

# **📜 What's Happening?**

| Part | Meaning |
| ----- | ----- |
| `docker run` | Create and run a new container. |
| `-d` | Run in **detached mode** (in background). |
| `--name test-mongo` | Name the container **`test-mongo`** for easy reference. |
| `-p 27018:27017` | Map **local port 27018** to **container port 27017** (MongoDB default port). |
| `-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_USERNAME=root` | Set an **environment variable** inside container: Root username \= `root`. |
| `-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_PASSWORD=example` | Set another **environment variable**: Root password \= `example`. |
| `mongo` | Use the official **MongoDB** image to create the container. |

---

# **🧩 Why `-e` (Environment Variables)?**

* The `-e` flag sets **environment variables** inside the container when it starts.

* MongoDB **needs a root user** and **root password** when **authentication** is enabled.

* `MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_USERNAME` and `MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_PASSWORD` are **special variables** understood by the official MongoDB image to create a database admin at startup.

✅ **Without these**, the MongoDB inside Docker will **NOT** have authentication setup.

# **📌 Real Example**

Connect after running:

`mongo --port 27018 -u root -p example --authenticationDatabase admin`

(You must mention `admin` database because the root user is created in `admin`.)

# **🐳 Docker Volume Commands**

Docker **volumes** are used to **persist data** outside the container’s filesystem.  
 (Containers are temporary, but volumes can store data even if containers are deleted.)

---

## **1️⃣ `docker volume ls`**

### **🔹 Purpose:**

List all **Docker volumes** on your system.

### **🔹 Usage:**

`docker volume ls`

### **🔹 Output:**

It shows a table like:

| DRIVER | VOLUME NAME |
| ----- | ----- |
| local | my\_mongo\_volume |
| local | another\_volume |

*   
  **DRIVER**: Usually `local` (default driver).

* **VOLUME NAME**: Name of the volume (automatically or manually named).

---

## **2️⃣ `docker volume inspect <volume_name>`**

### **🔹 Purpose:**

Show **detailed information** about a specific volume.

### **🔹 Usage:**

`docker volume inspect my_mongo_volume`

### **🔹 Output:**

Shows details in JSON format, like:

`[`  
  `{`  
    `"Name": "my_mongo_volume",`  
    `"Driver": "local",`  
    `"Mountpoint": "/var/lib/docker/volumes/my_mongo_volume/_data",`  
    `"CreatedAt": "2025-04-29T04:15:45Z",`  
    `...`  
  `}`  
`]`

🔵 **Mountpoint** tells where the volume is physically stored on your host machine.

---

## **3️⃣ `docker volume rm <volume_name>`**

### **🔹 Purpose:**

**Delete** a specific Docker volume.

### **🔹 Usage:**

`docker volume rm my_mongo_volume`

🔴 **Important**:

* Volume must **not** be **in use** by any container.

* Otherwise, Docker will throw an error.

* Safest to stop and remove containers using that volume before deleting.

---

## **4️⃣ `docker volume prune -a`**

🔵 Small correction:  
 ✅ The correct form is:

`docker volume prune`

(There’s **no `-a` option** for `docker volume prune`; it's optional for other prune commands like containers, images.)

### **🔹 Purpose:**

**Remove all unused volumes** (not used by any running/stopped container).

### **🔹 Usage:**

`docker volume prune`

Docker will ask for confirmation:

`WARNING! This will remove all unused volumes.`  
`Are you sure you want to continue? [y/N]`

Type `y` to confirm.

## **🔍 Key Components:**

| Flag | Purpose |
| ----- | ----- |
| `--name test-mongo` | Names the container for easy reference. |
| `-d` | Run in background (detached). |
| `-p 27018:27017` | Maps host port 27018 → container's MongoDB port 27017\. |
| `-v .mongo-data/data:/data/db` | Mounts local folder (`.mongo-data/data`) to MongoDB's **database storage path**. |
| `-v .mongo-data/config:/data/configdb` | Mounts local folder to MongoDB’s **config database path**. |
| `-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_USERNAME=root` | Sets root user. |
| `-e MONGO_INITDB_ROOT_PASSWORD=example` | Sets root password. |
| `mongo` | Base image to use (official MongoDB image). |

---

## **🧠 Why Use `-v` in Docker? (Real Explanation)**

By **default**, when you run a container, **all data is stored *inside* the container**.  
 But when the container is deleted, 🗑️ **the data is deleted too**.

That’s a big problem for databases like MongoDB — because you don’t want to lose your data every time you restart.

---

## **💡 `-v` Solves That Problem\!**

When you use `-v`, you are telling Docker:

“Please **store this data in my local folder on my computer**, not inside the container.”

So even if the container dies or gets deleted, your **data is still safe** in your local folder.

---

### **✅ Example from Your Script**

bash  
CopyEdit  
`-v .mongo-data/data:/data/db`  
`-v .mongo-data/config:/data/configdb`

This means:

| Local Folder | Inside Container Folder | Purpose |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| `.mongo-data/data` | `/data/db` | MongoDB stores **all database data** here |
| `.mongo-data/config` | `/data/configdb` | MongoDB stores **config info** here |

Now, MongoDB will **read/write data** to your real computer folders:

* On your machine: `project/.mongo-data/data`

* Inside container: `/data/db`

If the container is deleted or crashes:

* ✅ Data still remains in `.mongo-data/data` and `.mongo-data/config`

* 🔄 You can restart the container, and MongoDB picks up where it left off

## **📦 Dockerfile (Node.js project)**

`FROM node:20-alpine`  
`WORKDIR /code`

`ADD package.json .`  
`ADD yarn.lock .`  
`RUN yarn install`

`COPY . .`

`EXPOSE 5000`  
`CMD ["yarn", "dev"]`

### **🧾 Line-by-Line Breakdown**

| Line | Explanation |
| ----- | ----- |
| `FROM node:20-alpine` | Use a small, fast Node.js base image (Alpine \= minimal Linux). |
| `WORKDIR /code` | Sets the working directory inside the container. |
| `ADD package.json .` and `ADD yarn.lock .` | Copy dependency files first (for caching). |
| `RUN yarn install` | Install project dependencies. |
| `COPY . .` | Copy all files from your project into the container. |
| `EXPOSE 5000` | Tell Docker this container listens on port 5000\. |
| `CMD ["yarn", "dev"]` | Run `yarn dev` when the container starts (entrypoint). |

## **📁 Understanding `WORKDIR` in Docker**

### **🔹 What is `WORKDIR`?**

In a Dockerfile, the `WORKDIR` instruction sets the working directory for any subsequent instructions like `RUN`, `CMD`, `COPY`, and `ADD`. If the specified directory doesn't exist, Docker will create it within the container's filesystem.

For example:

dockerfile  
CopyEdit  
`WORKDIR /code`

This sets `/code` as the working directory inside the container. Any subsequent commands will operate relative to this directory.

### **🔹 Does `WORKDIR` Create a Folder on the Host?**

No, the `WORKDIR` instruction affects the container's internal filesystem only. It does **not** create a directory on your host machine. The directory `/code` exists **inside** the container and is isolated from your host's filesystem.

---

## **🖥️ Host vs. Container Filesystem**

* **Host Filesystem**: This is your local machine's filesystem. Unless you explicitly map directories between the host and the container, they remain separate.

* **Container Filesystem**: Each Docker container has its own isolated filesystem. The `WORKDIR` sets the working directory within this environment.

ADD package.json .  
ADD yarn.lock .

COPY . .

## **🐳 Dockerfile Breakdown**

`FROM node:20-alpine`

* **Purpose**: Sets the base image for your Docker container.

* **Effect**: Uses the official Node.js version 20 image built on Alpine Linux, which is a lightweight distribution. This results in smaller image sizes and faster downloads.​[Docker Documentation](https://docs.docker.com/get-started/docker-concepts/building-images/writing-a-dockerfile/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

---

`WORKDIR /code`

* **Purpose**: Sets the working directory inside the container.

* **Effect**: All subsequent commands will be executed in the `/code` directory within the container. If this directory doesn't exist, it will be created.​

---

`ADD package.json .`  
`ADD yarn.lock .`

* **Purpose**: Adds the `package.json` and `yarn.lock` files to the container.

* **Effect**: Copies these files from your local machine to the `/code` directory in the container. This is done before copying the entire application to leverage Docker's caching mechanism, ensuring that dependencies are only reinstalled when these files change.​

---

`RUN yarn install`

* **Purpose**: Installs the project dependencies defined in `package.json`.

* **Effect**: Uses Yarn to install all necessary packages, creating a `node_modules` directory in the container. This ensures that your application has all it needs to run.​

---

`COPY . .`

* **Purpose**: Copies the rest of your application code into the container.

* **Effect**: Transfers all files from your local project directory to the `/code` directory in the container, excluding files listed in `.dockerignore`.​

---

`EXPOSE 5000`

* **Purpose**: Informs Docker that the container will listen on port 5000 at runtime.

* **Effect**: This is mainly for documentation purposes and doesn't actually publish the port. To make the application accessible, you'll need to map the port when running the container using the `-p` flag (e.g., `-p 5000:5000`).​

---

`CMD ["yarn", "dev"]`

* **Purpose**: Specifies the default command to run when the container starts.

* **Effect**: Executes `yarn dev`, which typically starts your development server. This command can be overridden when running the container if needed.​

---

## **🔄 Flow Summary**

1. **Base Image**: Start with a lightweight Node.js environment.

2. **Set Working Directory**: Define where application code will reside in the container.

3. **Add Dependency Files**: Copy `package.json` and `yarn.lock` to leverage caching.

4. **Install Dependencies**: Run `yarn install` to set up the project environment.

5. **Copy Application Code**: Transfer the rest of your application into the container.

6. **Expose Port**: Declare the port your application will use.

7. **Define Startup Command**: Set the default command to start your application.​

---

## **📝 Additional Notes**

* **Alpine Linux**: Using Alpine reduces the image size, leading to faster builds and deployments. However, some packages may require additional configuration due to Alpine's minimalistic nature.

* **Yarn vs. npm**: Yarn is chosen here for its speed and deterministic dependency resolution. Ensure that your project is compatible with Yarn.

* **.dockerignore**: It's good practice to include a `.dockerignore` file to prevent unnecessary files (like `node_modules`, logs, etc.) from being copied into the container, which can bloat the image size.

# Sample backend dockerfile

FROM node:20-alpine

WORKDIR /app

\# Copy package files  
COPY package\*.json ./

\# Install dependencies  
RUN npm ci \--only=production

\# Copy source code  
COPY . .

\# Create uploads directory  
RUN mkdir \-p uploads

\# Expose port  
EXPOSE 4000

\# Add healthcheck  
HEALTHCHECK \--interval\=30s \--timeout\=3s \--start-period\=5s \--retries\=3 \\  
 CMD curl \-f http://localhost:4000/ || exit 1

\# Start the application  
CMD \["npm", "run", "start"\]

explain line by line with explanation as a beginner

---

## 1\. FROM node:20-alpine

* What it does:  
  This tells Docker to use the official Node.js version 20 image based on Alpine Linux as the starting point for your container.  
* Why:  
  Alpine is a small, lightweight Linux distribution, so your container will be smaller and faster.

---

## 2\. WORKDIR /app

* What it does:  
  Sets the working directory inside the container to /app.  
* Why:  
  All following commands will run in this directory. It helps organize your application files.

---

## 3\. COPY package\*.json ./

* What it does:  
  Copies package.json and package-lock.json (if it exists) from your project into the container’s /app directory.  
* Why:  
  These files list your app’s dependencies. Copying them first helps Docker cache this step, so you don’t have to reinstall dependencies every time you change your source code.

---

## 4\. RUN npm ci \--only=production

* What it does:  
  Installs only the production dependencies listed in package.json using the npm ci command.  
* Why:  
  This is faster and more reliable than npm install for production, and it skips installing devDependencies, making your image smaller and safer.

---

## 5\. COPY . .

* What it does:  
  Copies all remaining files from your project into the container’s /app directory.  
* Why:  
  This brings in your application’s source code and other needed files.

---

## 6\. RUN mkdir \-p uploads

* What it does:  
  Creates a directory called uploads inside /app.  
* Why:  
  Your app might need a place to save uploaded files. The \-p flag ensures the directory is created if it doesn’t exist.

---

## 7\. EXPOSE 4000

* What it does:  
  Tells Docker that your app will listen on port 4000\.  
* Why:  
  This is informational for Docker and tools that manage containers, so they know which port to connect to.

---

## 8\. HEALTHCHECK \--interval=30s \--timeout=3s \--start-period=5s \--retries=3 \\ CMD curl \-f http://localhost:4000/ || exit 1

* What it does:  
  Sets up a health check for your container:  
  * Every 30 seconds, Docker runs curl \-f http://localhost:4000/.  
  * If it fails, it tries again up to 3 times, with a 3-second timeout.  
  * It waits 5 seconds before starting the first check.  
* Why:  
  This helps Docker know if your app is running correctly. If it fails too many times, Docker can restart the container.

---

## 9\. CMD \["npm", "start"\]

* What it does:  
  Sets the default command to run when the container starts: npm start.  
* Why:  
  This starts your Node.js application as defined in your package.json file.

# Sample frontend dockerfile

FROM node:20-alpine as build

WORKDIR /app

\# Copy package files  
COPY package\*.json ./

\# Install dependencies  
RUN npm ci

\# Copy source code  
COPY . .

\# Build arguments  
ARG REACT\_APP\_BASE\_URL  
ARG REACT\_APP\_GOOGLE\_CLIENT\_ID  
ENV REACT\_APP\_BASE\_URL\=${REACT\_APP\_BASE\_URL}  
ENV REACT\_APP\_GOOGLE\_CLIENT\_ID\=${REACT\_APP\_GOOGLE\_CLIENT\_ID}

\# Build the app  
RUN npm run build

\# Production stage  
FROM nginx:alpine

\# Copy built app to nginx  
COPY \--from\=build /app/build /usr/share/nginx/html

\# Copy nginx configuration  
COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

EXPOSE 80

CMD \["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"\]

`ENV REACT_APP_BASE_URL=${REACT_APP_BASE_URL}`  
`ENV REACT_APP_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=${REACT_APP_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID}`

* ARG defines build-time variables that can be passed when building the image.  
* ENV sets environment variables inside the container, using the values from the build arguments. These are used by your React app (for example, to set API URLs or third-party service keys).

text

`# Build the app`  
`RUN npm run build`

* Runs the build script defined in your package.json. For React apps, this creates a production-ready set of static files in the build folder.

---

## Production Stage

text

`FROM nginx:alpine`

* Starts a new stage using the official Nginx web server image (also based on Alpine Linux, so it’s small and efficient).

text

`# Copy built app to nginx`  
`COPY --from=build /app/build /usr/share/nginx/html`

* Copies the static files produced in the build stage into the folder Nginx serves by default (/usr/share/nginx/html). The \--from=build means it takes the files from the "build" stage defined earlier.

text

`# Copy nginx configuration`  
`COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf`

* Copies your custom Nginx configuration file into the container, replacing the default config. This lets you control how Nginx serves your app.

text

`EXPOSE 80`

* Informs Docker that the container will listen on port 80, which is the standard HTTP port.

text

`CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]`

* Sets the default command to start Nginx in the foreground (so the container keeps running).
